				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Identity of inserts in pRtcB , pRtcR , and pRtcRDN was verified by sequencing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both probes identiÔ¨Åed the same proteins : AtoC , the product of b1201 , FhlA , HyfR , NRI , PrpR , PspF , RtcR , YfhA YgaA , YgeV , and ZraR ( HydH ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>The observation that overexpression of the N-terminally truncated but not full-length RtcR induces transcription of rtcA and rtcB suggests that , as in the case of several previously characterized s54-specific regulators ( e.g. XylR , DmpR , DctD , and LevR ( 66 -- 69 ) ) , the N-terminal domain represses activity of RtcR , and its deletion makes the regulator constitutively active .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">RtcR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>pRtcRDN , expressing the N-terminally truncated mutant of RtcR , was constructed similarly except that the HindIII site was introduced 21 nucleotides upstream of the beginning of the region encoding the central domain of RtcR ( the translation product starts with MTMITPLDFLKSG ... ; the first L residue shown in italics corresponds to amino acid 179 of RtcR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>The central domain of RtcR shows 28 -- 39 % identity and 56 -- 61 % similarity with counterparts in other regulators of this class and contains conserved regions C1 -- C7 found in other members of the family ( 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>Deletion of its ami-no-terminal domain also increases expression , which suggests that this domain inhibits the activity of RtcR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alignment of C-terminal domains of RtcR and a representative selection of known s54 regulators ( Fig. 5B ) suggests that RtcR has an atypical DNA-binding domain with the helix-turn-helix motif containing a 20-amino acid-long turn .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>B , alignment of the C-terminal portion of the putative DNA-binding domain of RtcR with a representative selection of other known s54-specific regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">RtcR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>The central-domain of RtcR shows 28 -- 39 % identity and 56 -- 61 % similarity with counterparts in other regulators of this class and contains conserved regions C1 -- C7 found in other members of the family ( 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>RtcR is not a member of the two-component system family of regulators ( 63 , 64 ) , so its activation is unlikely to involve phosphorylation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by RtcR</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>E. coli operons with conÔ¨Årmed 54-dependent promoters Promoter sequencea Operon Regulator Function argT-hisJQMP NRI-NRII Arginine , histidine-transport astCADBE NRI-NRII-ArgR Arginine catabolism atoDAEB AtoC-AtoS Acetoacetate-catabolism fdhF FhlA FDH glnALG NRI-NRII Nitrogen assimilation glnHPQ NRI-NRII Glutamine-transport glnK-amtB NRI-NRII PII paralog , NH3 transport hycABCDEFGHI FhlA Hydrogenase hydN-hypF FhlA Hydrogenase hypABCDE-fhlA FhlA Hydrogenase nac NRI-NRII Nitrogen assimilation prpBCDE PrpR Propionate catabolism pspABCDE PspF Phage shock and other stresses rtcBA RtcR RNA terminal cyclase ygjG NRI-NRII ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11528004" target="_blank">11528004</a>]<br></li>
<li>To investigate whether the RtcR regulator plays a role in expression of the cyclase operon , we have tested the effect of overexpression of wild-type and N-terminally truncated forms of RtcR on transcription of rtcA and rtcB in the strain YMC10 and its derivative YMC22 , containing the inactivated s54 gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have also established that the cyclase gene forms part of a so far uncharacterized operon , expression of which is controlled by s54 and the transcriptional regulator RtcR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9738023" target="_blank">9738023</a>]<br></li>
